<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-202-614  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 202 614.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  April 17 1989 n216 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>HP deals enterprising alternative. (Hewlett-Packard'sworkstations)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Colonna, Jerome D.; Meyers, Kara; Pelton, Charles; Sabatini,Stephen; Von Simpson, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Hewlett-Packard announced plans of the largest merger yet in theworkstation market, its acquisition of Apollo Computer for $476.4million.andP;  Workstation vendors are actively readjusting productstrategies in the volatile workstation market.andP;  The benefits toMIS will be quicker, less expense workstations.andP;  The drawbacksinclude delays in the adoption of a microcomputer standards andlarge-scale integration.andP;  Observers see integration as the key tovendor success.andP;  Vendors have to sell the workstation to thebroader market, not just to the usual engineering markets.andP;  Thechallenge from the newly strengthened HP is expected to go slowuntil Apollo is fully absorbed into the company.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (acquisitions and mergers)Apollo Computer Inc. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Ticker:    HWP; APCI.andO;Topic:     AcquisitionWorkstationsMarketing StrategyMarket AnalysisMIS.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   (Events of the week in the workstation market). (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>